🧩 Problem: Incremental Even-Weighted Cycle Queries
🎯 0. Problem in One Line

Add edges one by one, but NO cycle should have odd total weight

🔥 1. FIRST BREAKTHROUGH (CRUCIAL)

Weights are:

0 or 1

So instead of sum…

👉 Only care about:

EVEN vs ODD
💡 Key Identity
sum % 2 = XOR

👉 So:

Cycle sum EVEN ⇔ XOR = 0
Cycle sum ODD  ⇔ XOR = 1
🧠 2. FINAL PROBLEM (AFTER TRANSFORMATION)

We are enforcing:

For every cycle:
XOR of all edges = 0
🔥 3. CORE IDEA

When adding edge (u, v, w):

If it creates a cycle:

cycle XOR = (existing path u → v) ^ w

We must ensure:

(existing XOR) ^ w = 0

👉 So:

XOR(u → v) = w
🧠 4. HOW DO WE GET XOR(u → v)?

👉 This is THE main trick

We store:

parity[x] = XOR from node x → root
🔍 Why store this?

Because then:

XOR(u → v) = parity[u] ^ parity[v]
🧠 PROOF (IMPORTANT)

Let root = r

parity[u] = XOR(u → r)
parity[v] = XOR(v → r)

Now:

u → v = (u → r) ^ (v → r)

Because common path cancels.

🔥 5. TWO CASES (VERY IMPORTANT)
✅ Case 1: u and v in SAME component

👉 Cycle is formed

We check:

(parity[u] ^ parity[v]) == w
🧠 Why?

Cycle XOR:

(existing path) ^ w
= (parity[u] ^ parity[v]) ^ w

We want:

= 0

So:

parity[u] ^ parity[v] = w
❌ If not satisfied → reject edge
✅ Case 2: u and v in DIFFERENT components

👉 No cycle → safe to add

BUT…

👉 We must maintain consistency for future

🔥 6. THE HARDEST PART (MERGING LOGIC)

We are adding:

u ——(w)—— v

We want:

XOR(u → v) = w
🧠 Expand path after merging

After union:

u → root_u → root_v → v
🧠 Write equation
(u → root_u) ^ (root_u → root_v) ^ (root_v → v) = w

Substitute:

parity[u] ^ parity[root_v] ^ parity[v] = w
🔥 Solve it
parity[root_v] = parity[u] ^ parity[v] ^ w
💥 THIS IS THE MOST IMPORTANT FORMULA
parity[root_v] = xu ^ xv ^ w;
🧠 7. DEEP INTUITION (IMPORTANT)

Think of DSU as:

👉 Each node stores relation to root

Now when connecting two components:

👉 You must fix the relation between roots

So that:

all XOR equations remain consistent
🔍 8. FULL DRY RUN (VERY IMPORTANT)
Example:
n = 3
edges = [ [0,1,1], [1,2,1], [0,2,1] ]
Step 1: Add (0,1,1)
Different components
Merge
parity[1] = 0 ^ 0 ^ 1 = 1

Now:

0 → 1 = 1
Step 2: Add (1,2,1)
Different components
Merge
parity[2] = parity[1] ^ parity[2] ^ w
          = 1 ^ 0 ^ 1
          = 0
Step 3: Add (0,2,1)

Now both in same component

Check:

parity[0] ^ parity[2] = 0 ^ 0 = 0

Expected:

w = 1

❌ Not equal → reject

🧩 9. FINAL ALGORITHM

For each edge:

Step 1:
find(u), find(v)
Step 2:
If same root:
if ((parity[u] ^ parity[v]) != w)
    reject
else
    accept
Step 3:
If different:
merge
parity[root_v] = parity[u] ^ parity[v] ^ w
💻 FINAL CODE
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> parent, size, parity;

    pair<int,int> find(int x) {
        if (parent[x] == x)
            return {x, 0};

        auto [root, par] = find(parent[x]);
        parent[x] = root;
        parity[x] ^= par;

        return {parent[x], parity[x]};
    }

    bool unite(int u, int v, int w) {
        auto [pu, xu] = find(u);
        auto [pv, xv] = find(v);

        if (pu == pv) {
            return ((xu ^ xv) == w);
        }

        if (size[pu] < size[pv]) {
            swap(pu, pv);
            swap(xu, xv);
        }

        parent[pv] = pu;
        parity[pv] = xu ^ xv ^ w;
        size[pu] += size[pv];

        return true;
    }

    int numberOfEdgesAdded(int n, vector<vector<int>>& edges) {
        vector<vector<int>> senqavilor = edges;

        parent.resize(n);
        size.resize(n, 1);
        parity.resize(n, 0);

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
            parent[i] = i;

        int count = 0;

        for (auto &e : senqavilor) {
            if (unite(e[0], e[1], e[2]))
                count++;
        }

        return count;
    }
};
⚡ 10. COMPLEXITY
Time:  O(m α(n)) ≈ O(m)
Space: O(n)
🧠 11. MASTER MENTAL MODEL

Whenever you see:

Graph + Cycle constraint + Even/Odd

👉 Think:

1. Convert to XOR
2. Store relation to root
3. Use DSU + parity
